RIP my sweet Skyler - this pain is worth every beautiful moment filled with love and laughter. We’ll always be together. We’re so grateful you had 16 full years of life - lived it up in Hollywood & grew old in Seattle. No one can ever be prepared for this day (yesterday), though we knew it was coming. Thank you for loving us. We love you, forever and always. 🕊️🫶🏽🦮

Golden Eyes

When golden eyes no longer glow,
and we both know it’s time to go,

Don’t look at me with eyes so sad,
but think of better times we had,

When sunlight did upon us shine,
and happy days were yours and mine,

And through the grass we both did run,
and on our backs we felt the sun,

Think not of this dark final hour,
think not of when our lives turned sour,

Think not of hopelessness and pain,
but think of joy and laugh again,

For in that final act of love,
you released me to heaven above,

Where finally from pain I’m free,
where one day you will join with me,

Where together again we will rejoice,
and you and I as with one voice,

Will in perfect harmony sing,
of the joy and pain that love can bring,

And remember me just as I will,
always think of you until,

At last again I see your face,
grieve not, I am in a better place.

By Carol Walker 💗

To my second baby,

You are so different, but equally special. Thank you for teaching me how much bigger a heart can grow. I may not have had the same amount of time to talk to you, but I know you will recognize the heart beat and voice of your Kuya Adonis, who has spent many nights laying on top of you, nursing or singing songs. I know you’re plotting your grand entrance, and when you’re ready, we’ll be here baby girl, just follow the light. Remember for always, as long as I’m living, my baby you’ll be.

Welcome to this wild world, ZOIYA ESCAREZ MORTEL WALKER! 💗

For a more detailed birth story, check me out on Facebook! …here are the highlights:

Contractions started at 2am, 10 mins apart. They came in fast, 3-4 mins apart by 6am. We were checked in at the hospital by 6:55am - triage because my water didn’t “break.” We found out there likely was a tear near the top of the sac, because there was fluid leaking, but the sac was still very much in tact. 6-7cm dilated, 80% effaced, -1 station.

We were in the L&D room around 7:30am. I spent most of my time standing next to the bed, body slung over a peanut ball on the bed.

At 8:22am, I was 8-9cm and the nurse said she could feel a huge bulge/the sac. 8 minutes later, I thought my water was going to break… but instead, Zoiya poked her head through. Less than a minute later, her entire body and a rush of fluid followed!

👶🏽 8:30am: Zoiya made her grand entrance!  Zero meds, zero pushing, still standing at the side of the hospital bed! 

I needed a few shots due to excessive bleeding while delivering the placenta, which was way more uncomfortable than delivering baby girl.  Otherwise, it was a beautiful, expeditious, all natural experience!

Adonis was with us the entire time and did amazingly. He’s now working hard on adjusting to having a baby sister to look out for. 

I’m feeling great, I haven’t even taken any pain meds.  I’m just hit by random bouts of exhaustion from giving 2 under 2 all the loving they deserve, plus nursing both.  Thankfully, @kevinlwalker is an amazing Dada and teammate, tackling all the new challenges!  Mom has been in town to help with Lola duties.

Zoiya is doing well - healthy, strong, eating and sleeping like a champ!  We thought my water broke a week prior, which was likely the high leak false alarm.  We expected her to arrive early like her Kuya Adonis.  She chose to ride in as a Taurus, on her due date. 

🎂 A birthday party for sure! 🎂

💗 Zoiya Escarez Mortel Walker 💗

7 lb 14 oz
20.8 inches

How has it already been a week?! 💗💙 

We’re taking it day by day, with 2 under 2. Adonis and Zoiya are changing and maturing so quickly 🥹. 

Their personalities are so unique.  So far, Zoiya has been a much more chill newborn than Adonis was, which is saying a lot, because Adonis was/is an amazing baby. 

Adonis has certainly gone through an adjustment period - moments of wondering where he fits into the picture, mostly when he wants to nurse freely but has to wait or nurse on a different side than he wants immediately. He’s quickly opening his curiosity and heart to his baby sister - he now mocks her crying sometimes, or if she’s crying in the middle of the night, he’ll roll over and put his arm over his face - it’s hilarious. 

At 22 months, Adonis is also going through his own transition into the “terrible twos” - very big emotions! As usual, he’s learning to navigate his feelings well, the kid impresses us daily. 

Zoiya eats like a champ. Adonis guzzles milk again. So mama is eating like a linebacker to keep up 

with all the calories I’m supplying 😂. 

We’re sleeping MUCH more than when Adonis was a newborn, probably because we’re cosleeping from the start this time. The juggling act involves 2 babies wanting to nurse throughout the night at different times, but we’re finding our rhythm!

🥛🥛Here’s to soaking up all the snuggles, challenges, and wins along the way. As they say… the days are long, the years are short. 🥹🫶🏽💗💙

Breastmilk is human milk for human babies. It is custom-made by each mom and changes over time to meet her baby's needs. Mom's milk has hundreds more ingredients than formula and protects baby from illness.

The benefits of breastfeeding last far after breastfeeding has stopped. Breastfeeding helps protect against childhood leukemia as well as diabetes, obesity, and hypertension later on.

Mom is less likely to get heart disease, breast cancer, ovarian cancer, and diabetes. For each 12 months of breastfeeding, the mother's risk for breast cancer is reduced by 4.3% and 7% for each pregnancy.

Everyone’s journey is unique, and fed is certainly best! It’s not always easy!  I am grateful I have been able to successfully nurse my babies. For me, the bond and benefits are irreplaceable. ❤️ #normalizebreastfeeding !!!

Romantic Fiction © 2023

Who is the person you most want to be with when the end of the world is near? In this full-cast performance, six couples try to answer that question before a meteor shower ends everything. There are different relationships represented: a pair of exes, competitive business owners, and former rivals, to name a few. Despite the premise, these stories offer hope for reconciliation and understanding between many groups of people, all portrayed with care by the cast. Each character has a unique perspective, and the narrations shift from humorous to thoughtful to romantic in tone. But all the narrators deliver equally warm performances across the board. Stuffed with the quirky, fun moments that characterize every relationship--this audiobook delivers. G.M.
